        { "type": "post", "settings": { "category": "MINDSET", "title": "Consistency Over Motivation", "excerpt": "Why showing up every day matters more than feeling ready.", "content": "Motivation is unreliable. It comes and goes with mood, weather, sleep, and what you ate for breakfast.\n\nConsistency is the opposite. It doesn’t care how you feel. It just shows up.\n\nThis is the post-it on the bathroom mirror moment — the boring truth that nobody wants to hear because it’s not exciting. There is no shortcut. There is no perfect routine. There is only doing the work, day after day, even when you don’t feel like it.\n\nThat’s the whole game.", "read_time": "5 min read" } },
        { "type": "post", "settings": { "category": "NUTRITION", "title": "Protein: How Much Do You Really Need?", "excerpt": "Simple guide to hitting your protein goals without overthinking.", "content": "Most people massively overcomplicate protein.\n\nA simple rule: aim for around 1.6–2.2g of protein per kg of body weight if you’re training hard. For a 70kg person, that’s roughly 110–155g a day.\n\nThat sounds like a lot — until you realize a chicken breast has 30g, a cup of dal has 18g, and a scoop of whey has 24g. Three solid meals plus one snack and you’re there.\n\nDon’t obsess. Don’t weigh every gram. Just make sure protein shows up in every meal.", "read_time": "6 min read" } },
